# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amersfoort
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] The **Wallis Annenberg Building** (originally the **160th Regiment State Armory**, and also referred to as the **Exposition Park Armory**) is a building located in Exposition Park, Los Angeles, California.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] It was built in 1912 and designed by architect J.W.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] The armory hosted the fencing competition at the 1932 Summer Olympics as well as the fencing part of the modern pentathlon.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] It also served as an exposition hall and ballroom during the early- and mid-20th century.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] In 1947, the armory was converted into a bowling alley and hosted a tournament of the American Bowling Congress.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] It later served as a roller derby venue.
[src:amersfoort/160th-regiment-state-armory] The building is currently an annex of the California Science Center, serving as the Science Center School and the Amgen Center for Science Learning since 2004.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The **1928 Summer Olympics** (Dutch: *Olympische Zomerspelen 1928*), officially the **Games of the IX Olympiad** (Dutch: *Spelen van de IXe Olympiade*), was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated from 28 July to 12 August 1928 in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The city of Amsterdam had previously bid for the 1920 and 1924 Olympic Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Still, it was obliged to give way to war-torn Antwerp in Belgium for the 1920 Games and Pierre de Coubertin's Paris for the 1924 Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The only other candidate city for the 1928 Olympics was Los Angeles, which would eventually be selected to host the Olympics four years later.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] In preparation for the 1932 Summer Olympics, the United States Olympic Committee reviewed the costs and revenue of the 1928 Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The committee reported a total cost of US$1.183 million with receipts of US$1.165 million, giving a negligible loss of US$18,000, which was a considerable improvement over the 1924 Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and medals overall.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Dutch nobleman Frederik van Tuyll van Serooskerken first proposed Amsterdam as the host city for the Summer Olympic Games in 1912, even before the Netherlands Olympic Committee was established.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Olympic Games were canceled in 1916 due to World War I.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] In 1919, the Netherlands Olympic Committee abandoned the proposal of Amsterdam in favor of their support for the nomination of Antwerp as host city for the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] In 1921, Paris was selected for the 1924 Summer Olympics on the condition that the 1928 Summer Olympics would be organized in Amsterdam.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] This decision, supported by the Netherlands Olympic Committee, was announced by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) on 2 June 1921.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Los Angeles' bid for the 1928 Summer Olympics was unsuccessful in 1922 and again in 1923.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The city was eventually selected as host city for the 1932 Summer Olympics, being the only bidder for that year.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] During the 1928 Summer Olympics, there were 14 sports, 20 disciplines and 109 events in the tournament.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] In parentheses is the number of events per discipline.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Women's athletics and team gymnastics debuted at these Olympics, in spite of criticism.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Five women's athletics events were added: 100 meters, 800 meters, high jump, discus, and 400 meter hurdles.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] In protest of the limited number of events, British women athletes, boycotted the Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Halina Konopacka of Poland became the first female Olympic track and field champion.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Reports that the 800 meter run ended with several of the competitors being completely exhausted were widely (and erroneously) circulated.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] As a result, the IOC decided that women were too frail for long-distance running, and women's Olympic running events were limited to 200 meters until the 1960s.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Tennis disappeared from the program until it reappeared in 1968 as a demonstration sport.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] These Games also included art competitions in five categories: architecture, painting, sculpture, literature, and music.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] However, the IOC no longer considers these to be official medal events, so the medals awarded are not included in today's Olympic medal counts.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Fourteen sports venues were used for the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Swim Stadium was demolished in 1929.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Het Kasteel football stadium was renovated in 1998–99.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Monnikenhuize stadium was demolished in 1950.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Schermzaal sports hall has also been demolished.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was renovated between 1996 and 2000, and is still in use.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The Old Stadion was demolished in 1929 and replaced with housing in the Amsterdam area.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Many cars were expected for the Games, but Amsterdam had at most 2,000 single-car parking spaces.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Consequently, several new parking sites were provided, and a special parking symbol was launched to show foreign visitors where they could park.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The white P on a blue background was to become the international traffic sign for parking, and is still used today.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Athletics events were held on a 400-meter track, later becoming the standard for athletics tracks.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Map of the Amsterdam region with Olympic venues marked.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Map of the Netherlands with Olympic venues marked.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] A total of 46 nations were represented at the Amsterdam Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Malta, Panama, and Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe) competed at the Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Germany returned after having been banned in 1920 and 1924.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The nations that participated in the previous games in Paris 1924 but were absent in Amsterdam 1928 were Brazil and Ecuador.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, South Africa and Ireland were all dominions of the British Empire.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] India and Rhodesia were also a part of the British Empire, but were not dominions.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] United States, France, Argentina, Japan, etc.) and the international community as a whole (i.e.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] League of Nations) the term dominion, used internally in the British Empire, was very ambiguous, meaning "something between a colony and state".
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] It was only years later with the Statute of Westminster 1931 that this ambiguity would be dispelled.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Philippines was an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1928 Games.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The official poster for the Games displaying a running man in a white shirt was designed by Jos Rovers however the IOC never succeeded in obtaining the copyright of the image.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The IOC used a different poster, with the German text *Olympische Spiele*, and an athlete partly covered in the Dutch national flag, holding a peace leaf in his hand.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The poster was made for a German book about the Amsterdam Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] The last living competitor of the 1928 Summer Olympics was Carla Marangoni, a member of the silver medal-winning Italian gymnastic team who had been twelve years old during the Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/1928-summer-olympics] Marangoni died 18 January 2018, at the age of 102 as the oldest living Olympic medalist at the time of her death.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The **2028 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXXIV Olympiad** and commonly known as **Los Angeles 2028** or **LA28**, is an upcoming international multi-sport event scheduled to take place from July 14 to 30, 2028, in the United States.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will be the host city, with various events also scheduled to be held at other cities spread across the Greater Los Angeles area, plus two subsites in Oklahoma City.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles had originally bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Following multiple withdrawals, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) approved a process to concurrently award the 2024 and 2028 Games to Los Angeles and Paris as the two remaining candidates; Paris was preferred as host for 2024, while Los Angeles agreed to host in 2028.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was formally awarded the Games at the 131st IOC Session in Lima, Peru, on September 13, 2017.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] They will mark the fifth Summer Olympics, and ninth Olympics overall to be hosted by the United States.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles has previously hosted the Summer Olympics in 1932 and 1984, and will become the third three-time host city after London (1908, 1948, 2012) and Paris (1900, 1924, 2024), and the first non-European city to do so.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] These will be the first Summer Olympics held under the IOC presidency of Kirsty Coventry.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] After debuting in 2020 as optional events, skateboarding, sport climbing, and surfing have been promoted to the Summer Olympics' core event program.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Games will feature the debut of flag football and squash as optional sports, joined by the return of baseball/softball, cricket (for the first time since 1900) and lacrosse (for the first time as a medal event since 1908).
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On September 16, 2015, the International Olympic Committee announced the candidature process and the five candidate cities for the 2024 Games: Budapest, Hamburg, Los Angeles, Paris, and Rome.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Budapest, Hamburg, and Rome eventually withdrew, leaving only Los Angeles and Paris.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] A similar situation had already occurred during the bidding for the 2022 Winter Olympics when Kraków, Lviv, Oslo, and Stockholm withdrew, resulting in a two-way decision between Beijing, China, and Almaty, Kazakhstan, with Beijing ultimately declared the winner.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On April 3, 2017, at the IOC convention in Denmark, Olympic officials met with bid committees from Los Angeles and Paris to discuss the possibility of naming two winners in the competition to host the 2024 Summer Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] After these withdrawals, the IOC Executive Board met in Lausanne, Switzerland, on June 9, 2017, to discuss the 2024 and 2028 bid processes.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The IOC formally proposed electing the 2024 and 2028 host cities at the same time in 2017, a proposal that an Extraordinary IOC Session approved on July 11, 2017, in Lausanne.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The IOC set up a process where the Los Angeles and Paris 2024 bid committees and the IOC held meetings in July 2017 to decide which city would host in each of the two years.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Following the decision to award the 2024 and 2028 Games simultaneously, Paris was understood to be preferred for the 2024 Games, as it would also mark the centennial of the 1924 Summer Olympics in Paris.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On July 31, 2017, the IOC announced Los Angeles as the sole candidate for 2028, with $1.8 billion of additional funding from the IOC, allowing Paris to be confirmed as the host for 2024.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On August 11, 2017, the Los Angeles City Council voted unanimously to approve the bid.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On September 11, 2017, Los Angeles received formal approval from the IOC's evaluation commission.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On September 13, 2017, Los Angeles was formally awarded the 2028 Games following a unanimous vote by the IOC.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] IOC president Thomas Bach praised the LA bid for using a record-breaking number of existing and temporary facilities and for relying entirely on private funding.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On October 16, 2017, LA 2028 received official endorsement from the state of California.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On August 29, 2018, Olympic officials arrived for a two-day visit that included meetings with local organizers and a tour of the city's newest venues.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] At the time, LMU and *LA Times* polls stated that more than 88% of Angelenos were in favor of the city hosting the 2028 Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In March 2023, a poll conducted by Suffolk University and the *LA Times* indicated 57% of Angelenos believed the Olympics would be good for the city, while 20% indicated they thought it would have a negative impact.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles civic leaders initially announced a plan to make the 2028 Olympics "car-free", aiming to reduce congestion, shorten travel times, and comply with security restrictions that limit parking near venues.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Twenty-eight by '28 initiative, launched by former Mayor Eric Garcetti, aimed to complete 28 infrastructure projects before the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Most projects were already in planning stages, but the initiative accelerated their completion.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Funding comes from Measure R and Measure M, countywide sales tax measures.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Mayor Karen Bass also promoted strategies such as encouraging remote work during the event to reduce demand on the transportation network.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] By March 2024, the original list of 28 projects was significantly revised, with 11 projects, including 5 rail line expansions, replaced by smaller projects considered more feasible to meet deadlines, including some projects that had already been completed.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] By late 2024, observers expressed concern that only 5.2% of LA Metro's $3.3 billion Olympic-related project list was funded, and several projects were running behind schedule.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Officials also noted uncertainties related to government agency staffing, interagency coordination, and the late finalization of the Olympic venue list.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] These challenges led civic leaders to pivot away from a fully "car-free" Games toward a "transit-first" approach.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Several major rail expansions are underway to support Olympic transportation.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Construction began in 2014 and remains largely on schedule.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Regional Connector, completed in 2023, links Metro's light rail lines in downtown Los Angeles, providing easier transfers between lines that serve Long Beach, the San Gabriel Valley, and Santa Monica, all of which will host Olympic competition venues.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The K Line, which opened in October 2022 after multiple delays, connects the Crenshaw District, Inglewood, and Westchester, and will connect with a people mover at LAX, which is projected to open in October 2026 after several postponements.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] While many venues are located near existing rail lines, Los Angeles lacks the continuous, high-capacity subway system that supported past Olympic Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Consequently, buses are expected to serve as the primary mode of transportation for most spectators.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Los Angeles Metro and Olympic organizers estimate that an additional 2,700 buses will be needed, effectively doubling the current Metro fleet of 2,320 vehicles.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Metro has requested that transit agencies nationwide donate buses near the end of their usable life for temporary Olympic service, potentially adding hundreds of vehicles.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Costs are estimated at $700 million to $1 billion, and through the Vision 2028 plan, Metro is seeking federal grants and coordinating post-Games resale of buses to other cities.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Building on the legacy of the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics–the first to generate a profit through innovative corporate sponsorship and private funding–the 2028 Los Angeles Games are heavily relying on a similar, fully private financial model.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In April 2019, the estimated cost of the Games was assessed as being approximately $6.88 billion, with all the money coming from the private sector.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The organizers adjusted the budget for inflation after LA, which originally bid for the 2024 Games, agreed to wait four more years.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The City of Los Angeles is the lead public guarantor, committing to spend up to $250 million to cover shortfalls.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In 2016, the California legislature took action so that the Governor is empowered to negotiate the next $250 million in public backup, but only after the city backup money has been used first.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] LA 2024 also agreed to purchase a wide range of insurance policies to cover financial relief in the event of natural disaster, terrorism, event cancellation, as well as reduced ticket sales.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Games are expected to generate as much as they cost, with $2.5 billion coming in through sponsorships and nearly $2 billion earned through ticket sales.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Average ticket prices for the Games will range between $13 and $457 (in 2016 dollars).
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Over $2 billion in sponsorships were secured by late 2025, surpassing the 2024 Paris Games more than two years early.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Olympics are the second to take place in the United States since the September 11 attacks in 2001.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Like the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City, which took place five months after that attack, the United States Department of Homeland Security will designate the Olympics a National Special Security Event (NSSE).
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Due to this designation, the United States Secret Service will be in charge of security and will head a single chain of command.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Casey Wasserman has stated that there will be no issues with the federal government on obtaining visas for athletes, security and delivery at the 144th IOC Session, emphasizing that they have received bipartisan support from all previous U.S. presidents, including Donald Trump.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] LA28 officials met with then President-elect Trump at Mar-a-Lago in January 2025 and his administration pledged to help Los Angeles recover from the wildfires, and hold "the greatest games".
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In July 2025, $1 billion in funding was earmarked for a Homeland Security Grant Program for federal security and planning costs as part of the One Big Beautiful Bill Act.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] ) will host the ceremonies, as well as the athletics and swimming events respectively.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Like the 1984 Summer Olympics, a majority of the 2028 Summer Olympics will be hosted in venues around the Greater Los Angeles area.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The city's bid relied primarily on existing venues and venues that had already been under construction or were planned regardless of the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The majority of venues were divided into clusters known as "sports parks" (changed to "zones" during the planning phase), situated in downtown Los Angeles, the San Fernando Valley, Carson (at California State University, Dominguez Hills), and Long Beach.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] No new permanent venues are being built specifically for the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Like the 1984 Summer Games, the Olympic Village will be situated on the University of California, Los Angeles campus, while the University of Southern California will host the Media Village.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum will host athletics and the Rose Bowl will host football (soccer), respectively.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Both will become the first stadiums to have ever hosted three different Olympic Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Crypto.com Arena will host gymnastics, and Intuit Dome will host basketball.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] BMO Stadium, which opened in 2018 as the home of Major League Soccer's Los Angeles FC, will host the flag football and lacrosse.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] SoFi Stadium, which opened in 2020 as the home of the NFL's Los Angeles Rams and Los Angeles Chargers, will host swimming events.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Coliseum underwent a major renovation and restoration program from 2017 to 2019.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] A new press box, loge boxes, and club seats were installed.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Crypto.com Arena underwent renovations completed in 2024, and the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers opened a new arena in Inglewood known as Intuit Dome the same year.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Cricket will be hosted at the Knight Riders Cricket Ground at the Fairplex in Pomona, California.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] To reduce costs and use more pre-existing facilities, LA28 announced changes to its venue plans in June 2024.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The temporary aquatics venue that was scheduled to be built at USC's Dedeaux Field was scrapped, in favor of holding swimming at SoFi Stadium and artistic swimming in Long Beach.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Diving was originally set for the historic LA84 Foundation/John C.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Argue Swim Stadium (which was built for the 1932 Games) but was changed in September 2025 to the Rose Bowl Aquatic Center in Pasadena due to cost and safety concerns.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] With a planned configuration for 38,000 spectators, SoFi Stadium will be the largest swimming venue in Olympic history.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Equestrian will return to Santa Anita Park once again, as Arcadia had previously hosted the event in 1984, while softball and canoe slalom were moved to existing venues in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, instead of building new venues in Los Angeles County.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In February 2026, the six preliminary association football (soccer) venues were announced.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The match schedule, which will be unveiled before April 2026, will allow the competition to progressively move east to west as teams advance to the final stages, minimizing travel demands.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Louis, San Jose and San Diego are the six cities outside of the LA area set to host football matches.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The match schedule, unveiled in March 2026, will allow the competition to progressively move east to west as teams advance to the final stages, minimizing travel demands.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In July 2025, LAOCOG CEO Reynold Hoover informed the California State Senate that the torch relay for LA 2028 planned to visit all 50 U.S. states, explaining that it would "bind the nation with LA and California".
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Registration for the first ticket lottery opened in January 2026, with selected fans being able to purchase tickets starting in March.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] An estimated 14 million tickets will be available to purchase for the Games, two million more than that of Paris 2024.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] 1 million tickets will start at $28, with a third being under $100.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The opening ceremonies will be held on July 14, 2028, and will be co-hosted by the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum and SoFi Stadium.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The Coliseum will also host the closing ceremonies.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Filmmaker and media executive Peter Rice was named "head of ceremonies and content" for LA 2028, overseeing the ceremonies for both the Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Wasserman did not specifically state a planned budget, but said that he would provide Rice with any resources he needs.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Ben Winston will serve as executive producer and creative director, alongside veteran ceremony producer Scott Givens; production will be overseen by FulFive, a joint venture between Winston and Given's respective companies Fulwell 73 and FiveCurrents.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The 2028 Summer Olympics is expected to include 353 medal events in 36 sports, an increase of 24 events and four sports over the 2024 Summer Olympics; this includes 31 mandatory "core" sports, and five optional sports that were proposed by LAOCOG to help improve local interest.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The core program consists of the 28 core sports contested since 2016, along with skateboarding, sport climbing, and surfing—three sports that have been officially promoted to the core program after being contested as optional sports in 2020 and 2024.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The five optional sports will include the Olympic debuts of flag football (a non-contact variant of gridiron football) and squash, the return of baseball/softball for the first time since 2020, the return of cricket for the first time since 1900, and lacrosse for the first time since 1908.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Cricket will consist of men's and women's tournaments using the Twenty20 (T20) format, with six teams each.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Flag football will consist of men's and women's tournaments.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On May 20, 2025, the National Football League announced that it had reached an agreement with its team owners to potentially allow their players to compete in the men's flag football tournament, pending agreements with the league's players' union.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In November 2025, the Canadian Football League (whose regular season falls during the Olympics) announced a similar allowance.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Lacrosse will utilize the lacrosse sixes format.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] World Lacrosse recognizes Haudenosaunee as a member and it has competed in world championships, but it does not have a National Olympic Committee; its players could still theoretically play for the Canada or the United States teams, but most have stated that they would only play for Haudenosaunee.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Of the 16 new disciplines proposed by existing Olympic sports, beach sprint rowing was the only one to be accepted by the IOC.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] It will replace the lightweight double sculls category, and consist of individual events for men and women as well as a mixed double sculls event.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon is expected to employ a new format which replaces show jumping with obstacle course racing.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In sport climbing, the combined boulder-and-lead event will be replaced by separate competitions for each discipline, expanding it to six medal events.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The men's football tournament will be reduced from 16 to 12 teams, while the marathon race walk mixed relay introduced in 2024 was dropped.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] With these changes, the 2028 Summer Olympics will be the first to have more female than male athletes.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On September 19, 2025, the IOC announced that weightlifting would be expanded to six bodyweight classes per-gender (with no change in athlete quota) to be better-aligned with the International Weightlifting Federation (IWF)'s new bodyweight classes, and disincentivize "extreme weight reduction".
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Since 2020, the program of the Summer Olympics has consisted of mandatory core sports that persist between Games, and up to six optional sports proposed by the organizing committee in order to improve local interest.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In August 2022, LAOCOG shortlisted nine proposed sports for consideration as optional events for these Olympics: baseball/softball, breaking (breakdance), cricket, flag football, karate, kickboxing, lacrosse, squash, and motorsport.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On October 9, 2023, LAOCOG announced that they had officially submitted baseball/softball, cricket, flag football, lacrosse, and squash for consideration by the IOC.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] All five sports were approved at the 141st IOC Session in Mumbai, India.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The IOC also reinstated modern pentathlon and weightlifting for the core program, citing that the sports' governing bodies had made sufficient efforts in carrying out reforms.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The IOC withheld a decision on boxing due to the IBA's expulsion and insufficient reach by World Boxing; in February 2025, the IOC granted provisional recognition to World Boxing, citing its progress on reach and commitments to integrity.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On March 20, 2025, at the 144th IOC Session in Greece, the IOC voted unanimously to approve a recommendation by the IOC Executive Board to reinstate boxing, with the event being sanctioned by World Boxing.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding the approval of cricket by the IOC, USA Cricket is not currently certified as a national governing body by the United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee (USOPC), which would be required in order for the sport to be contested.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The ICC has previously warned that USA Cricket's governance would need to be reformed in order to meet USOPC standards, and began a process to "reset" the organization to meet them.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] As of June 2026, the following eleven nations have qualified.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The United States' total reflects expected host country quota allocations.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In 2025, under the new leadership of Kirsty Coventry, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) is signaling a shift towards political neutrality by considering the return of Russia and Belarus to the Olympic Games, with both countries having been heavily restricted since 2022.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Despite the ongoing conflict between Russia and Ukraine, Coventry has expressed openness to revisiting Russia's and Belarus' participation.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On July 13, 2025, the Organizing Committee published the first version of the competition schedule.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On November 12, 2025, an updated comprehensive competition schedule by event was released, outlining when every medal event will take place during the upcoming Olympic Games in Los Angeles, with details across all confirmed sports and venues.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In order to facilitate use of SoFi Stadium for both the opening ceremonies and swimming, the scheduling of swimming and athletics events will be reversed.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Athletics events will take place during the first week of the Games, during which SoFi Stadium will be reconfigured to uncover the pool in preparation for swimming competition during the second week.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] This will be the first time since the 1968 Summer Olympics in Mexico City that athletics competitions will take place in the first week of the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On September 1, 2020, LAOCOG unveiled the emblem for the 2028 Summer Olympics, featuring the characters "LA" and "28" in a stacked layout.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The "A" in "LA" was designed to be interchangeable, with numerous variations created in collaboration with athletes, artists, designers, and celebrities, including Billie Eilish, Lilly Singh, and Reese Witherspoon.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The visual identity has also been used to promote official partners of the Games, such as Delta Air Lines and broadcaster NBC (which replaces the "A" with Delta's "widget" logo and the NBC peacock respectively).
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] LAOCOG chair Casey Wasserman stated that the variations were intended to "showcase our community's collective creativity and celebrate the diversity that makes us strong", reflecting a city that "defies a singular identity".
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Chief marketing officer Amy Gleeson said the emblem was designed to connect with an audience who will be in their 20s and 30s when the Games take place.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] On March 28, 2026, LAOCOG unveiled the overall branding elements of the Games, entitled "LA in full bloom", which were designed by Culver City-based agency Koto.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The branding utilizes shades taken from Los Angeles's official flower, the Strelitzia (Bird of paradise), including *poppy*, *scarlet flax*, *bluebell*, and *sagebrush.* The branding also incorporates several typefaces inspired by the city's street signage.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] LAOCOG partnered with NBCUniversal—owner of the U.S. media rights to the Olympics—to coordinate sponsorship sales for the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] As part of the agreement and its sponsorship with the United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee (USOPC), NBCU parent company Comcast will be billed as a "Founding Partner" of LA 2028.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] For the first time in Olympic and Paralympic history, venues will be permitted to carry naming rights during the Games, provided that their naming rights partner is a Worldwide Olympic Partner (WOP) or Founding Partner of LA28.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] The organising committee also plans to sell naming rights for the temporary venues.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] In January 2026, Comcast and NBCUniversal spun off CNBC, USA Network, and other cable operations into a new company called Versant, with an agreement being made for those cable channels to continue airing Olympics coverage.
[src:amersfoort/2028-summer-olympics] Hollywood Park Studios is planned to be the site of the International Broadcast Centre for the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The **2032 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXXV Olympiad** and also known as **Brisbane 2032**, is a planned international multi-sport event scheduled to take place from 23 July to 8 August 2032 in Brisbane, Australia, with venues across the various regions of Queensland.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] As part of the new Olympic bid process, the Future Host Commission of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) nominated Brisbane as its preferred candidate on 24 February 2021.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The Brisbane bid was approved on 21 July 2021 during the 138th IOC Session in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] It will be the third Olympic Games held in Australia, following the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne, Victoria, and the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, New South Wales; Melbourne and Sydney will host some events during the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] It will be held in Brisbane's winter, the second Summer Olympics held in the host city's winter after the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] It will also be the first Olympic Games since 2016 to take place in the southern hemisphere.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The new IOC bidding process was approved at the 134th IOC Session on 24 June 2019 in Lausanne, Switzerland.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The IOC also modified the Olympic Charter to increase its flexibility by removing the date of election from 7 years before the games and changing the host from a single city/region/country to multiple cities, regions, or countries.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The change in the bidding process was criticised by members of the German bid as "incomprehensible" and hard to surpass in "terms of non-transparency".
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] On 24 February 2021, the Future Host Commission named Brisbane as its preferred candidate for the 2032 Summer Olympics, and the IOC formally invited the Brisbane bid committee and Australian Olympic Committee to engage in targeted dialogue.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Committee chairwoman Kristin Kloster Aasen cited Brisbane's "high level of expertise in hosting major international sports events", the quality of its transport infrastructure (citing its performance during the 2018 Commonwealth Games), and a favourable climate.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] At the 138th IOC Session in Tokyo, Japan on 21 July 2021, the IOC's delegates passed a referendum to officially award the 2032 Summer Olympics to Brisbane.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] In the voting, 72 of the delegates voted "Yes", 5 voted "No" and 3 other voters abstained.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Having been awarded the hosting rights 11 years and 2 days in advance, this is the most time a host city has had in planning and organizing an Olympic Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The Brisbane Organising Committee for the 2032 Olympic and Paralympic Games, a statutory corporation, was established by the Queensland Government in 2021.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] It is governed by a board led by Andrew Liveris AO; its role is to plan, organise and deliver the Brisbane Olympic and Paralympic Games in accordance with the 'host contract' struck between Brisbane organisers and the IOC in 2021.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] From the 2021 selection of the city as the host for the 2032 Summer Olympics, Brisbane has 11 years to prepare for the games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] A feasibility study commissioned by the Southeast Queensland Council of Mayors in 2019 suggested that the Games could be a catalyst for increased transport and infrastructure investment.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Additionally, 68% of the required venues were judged to already exist or could be upgraded to an Olympic standard.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] It concluded that, excluding government agency costs and contributions by the IOC and the private sector, the Games net cost would be $900 million.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] This amount also did not include the suggested billions of dollars of greater investment in roads and public transport that would be required for the Games to be successful.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] In 2023, the federal and state governments reached a funding deal, with the Commonwealth contributing $2.5 billion for the Brisbane Live arena and $1 billion for other infrastructure.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The remaining costs would be borne by the Queensland Government.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The Games will use a mix of new, renovated, and expanded venues across Brisbane, Gold Coast, and the Sunshine Coast, Cairns, and Townsville, Queensland.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Melbourne and Sydney—Australia's two previous host cities in 1956 and 2000, respectively—will also host football preliminaries.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] A new 63,000-seat stadium will be built at Victoria Park, which will host the ceremonies and athletics events; it will replace Brisbane's historic Gabba stadium as the city's main facility for Australian rules football and cricket following the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The Centenary Pool Complex will be expanded with a new 25,000-seat aquatics centre, while the Queensland Tennis Centre will be expanded with 12 new courts and a 3,000-seat show court.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The Gabba was originally slated to be reconstructed to host the ceremonies and athletics, expanding it to 50,000 seats and adding a new pedestrian plaza.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The costs of the Gabba project were scrutinized by politicians; it was originally announced at a cost of $1 billion, but by February 2023, it had increased to $2.7 billion, which would be paid entirely by the state.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Scrutiny over the Gabba project grew after Victoria withdrew its hosting of the 2026 Commonwealth Games due to cost concerns.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] On 13 December 2023, Premier of Queensland Steven Miles announced the establishment of a Brisbane 2032 infrastructure authority, and an independent review of the Games' venue plans.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] On 18 March 2024, Miles announced that the Gabba reconstruction had been scrapped as a result, and that Lang Park (which is already scheduled to host rugby sevens and football) and Queensland Sport and Athletics Centre (QSAC) would respectively host the ceremonies and athletics instead.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Both venues would be refurbished, while reports that had been commissioned as part of the Gabba project would be used to guide future work on the stadium.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] A proposed 17,000-seat indoor arena known as Brisbane Live (which was slated to host swimming and water polo events) was also relocated to the Roma Street Parkland, rather than above the Roma Street railway station.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The review recommended the construction of a new 55,000-seat stadium at Victoria Park, but Miles stated he wanted Brisbane 2032 to be a "low-cost" Games, and that he could not justify a $3.4 billion stadium "when Queenslanders are struggling with housing and other costs".
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] On 29 October 2024, after the Liberal National Party of Queensland's victory in the state election, incoming Premier David Crisafulli announced that he would launch a 100-day independent review of the stadium proposals.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] This included the Gabba rebuild and Victoria Park stadium proposals, as well as new proposals sent in by numerous design firms.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The plan to have athletics at QSAC was scrapped.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] On 25 March 2025, Crisafulli announced that the state government would go ahead with plans for a 63,000-seat stadium at Victoria Park; the stadium will replace the Gabba, which will be demolished and redeveloped for a residential project following the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] He argued that "any other choice would have meant placing the government's interests ahead of the interests of Queensland" and felt that hosting athletics at QSAC would have been "embarrassing".
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Crisafulli apologized for breaking a campaign promise to not build a new stadium for the Olympics, stating that "I have to own that, and I will.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] I am sorry, it's my decision, and I accept that decision".
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] According to the review, the stadium will cost an estimated AU$3.8 billion, although this figure is yet to be publicly confirmed.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Brisbane Live was also scrapped in favour of building a new 25,000-seat aquatics centre at the Centenary Pool Complex; after the Games, the capacity would be reduced to 8,000.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The arena will be relocated to Woolloongabba across from the Gabba, and will continue as a standalone "market-led" project without federal funding.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] As of 2021, Brisbane has many infrastructure projects under construction or planning on top of the Games.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Cross River Rail, scheduled to be completed by 2029, is an underground railway project through central Brisbane, which is under construction.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Cross River Rail will see the development of a new rail line underneath Brisbane River, and the redevelopment of several stations in the Brisbane central business district with a cost of over A$17 billion.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Another transport infrastructure project is the Brisbane Metro bus rapid transit project, which consists of two routes with a headway of up to five minutes during peak times.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The project is scheduled to be completed in late 2024.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] In May 2024, funding was announced for the proposed Maroochydore railway line, expected to be completed by 2032.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Brisbane Lord Mayor Adrian Schrinner proposed in 2021 that a 7-hectare (17-acre) glass factory in West End formerly operated by Visy, be redeveloped into a 57,000 m2 (613,500 sq ft) International Broadcast Centre along the banks of the Brisbane River.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The main Athletes' Village will be located at Bowen Hills, with satellite villages in Royal Pines, Maroochydore, Rockhampton and Hervey Bay.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] In December 2025, the Queensland government appointed Unite32, a joint venture between AECOM and Laing O'Rourke, to be the delivery partner for the Games' infrastructure.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] The initial sports programme will be determined at an IOC Session in 2026.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Domestically, the Games will be televised by Nine Entertainment properties (including the Nine Network), which acquired the rights to the Olympics from 2024 through 2032 in a deal announced on 8 February 2023.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] These Games also mark the final year of the IOC's long-term broadcasting contracts with CMG in China, European Broadcasting Union/Warner Bros.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] Discovery in Europe, and NBCUniversal in the United States, among others.
[src:amersfoort/2032-summer-olympics] In March 2025, NBCU signed an extension to air the Olympics through the 2036 Games; the IOC is otherwise waiting "for the best market conditions" to sign new broadcasting deals.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The **24 Hours of Le Mans** (French: ***24 Heures du Mans***; French pronunciation: [vɛ̃t.katʁ‿œʁ dy mɑ̃]) is an endurance sports car race held annually near the city of Le Mans, France.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] First run in 1923, it is the oldest active endurance racing event in the world and is widely considered one of the world's most prestigious races.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is part of two informal "Triple Crown" series: the Triple Crown of Motorsport (with the F1 Monaco Grand Prix and the Indianapolis 500) and the Triple Crown of endurance racing (with the Florida-based 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Unlike fixed-distance races whose winner is determined by minimum time, the 24 Hours of Le Mans is won by the car that covers the greatest distance in 24 hours.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The cars on this track are able to achieve speeds of 366 km/h (227 mph), and reached 407 km/h (253 mph) on the main straight in 1988 – instigating the addition of more chicanes to the track to reduce speed reached.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Racing teams must balance the demands of speed with the cars' ability to run for 24 hours without mechanical failure.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is organized by the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is held on the Circuit de la Sarthe, composed of closed public roads and dedicated sections of a racing track.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was often part of the World Sportscar Championship from 1953 until that series' final season in 1992.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, it was a part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2012, the race has been a part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A 10-hour American version of the race, called Petit Le Mans, has been held annually since 1998.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most recent running of the event, the 94th 24 Heures du Mans, ran from 13 to 14 June 2026.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Launched when Grand Prix motor racing was the dominant form of motorsport throughout Europe, Le Mans was designed to present a different test.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Instead of focusing on the ability of a car company to build the fastest machines, the 24 Hours of Le Mans would concentrate on the ability of manufacturers to build sporty yet reliable cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This encouraged innovation in producing reliable and fuel-efficient vehicles, because endurance racing requires cars that last and spend as little time in the pits as possible.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, the layout of the track required cars with better aerodynamics and stability at high speeds.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While this was shared with Grand Prix racing, few tracks in Europe had straights of a length comparable to the *Ligne droite des Hunaudières*, often referred to as Mulsanne Straight after the village it leads to.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The oil crisis in the early 1970s led organizers to adopt a fuel economy formula known as Group C that limited the amount of fuel each car was allowed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it was later abandoned, fuel economy remains important as new fuel sources reduce the time spent during pit stops.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such technological innovations have had a trickle-down effect and can be incorporated into consumer cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has also led to faster and more exotic supercars as manufacturers seek to develop faster road cars in order to develop them into even faster GT cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2000s, hybrid systems (flywheel, super-capacitor, battery coupled with both petrol and diesel) have been championed in the Le Mans prototype category as rules have been changed to their benefit and to further push efficiency.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is held in mid-June, near the summer solstice, meaning the shortest night and very hot conditions for drivers, particularly in closed vehicles with poor ventilation.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race begins in mid-afternoon and finishes the following day at the same hour the race started the previous day.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2025 race attracted 332,000 spectators.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Modern competitors often cover well over 5,000 km (3,110 mi).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The record is 2010's 5,410 km (3,360 mi), more than six times the length of the Indianapolis 500 (500 mi or 805 km), or about 18 times longer than a Formula One *Grand Prix*.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers and their teams strive for speed and avoiding mechanical damage, as well as managing the cars' consumables – primarily fuel, tires, and braking materials.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It also tests endurance, with drivers frequently racing for over two hours before a relief driver can take over during a pit stop while eating and resting.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Current regulations mandate that three drivers share each competing vehicle, with individual limits of driving no more than 4 hours in a 6-hour period, and no more than 14 hours total.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Competing teams race in groups called "classes", or cars of similar specification, while competing simultaneously for outright placing amongst all classes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally, the race showcased cars as they were sold to the general public, then called "Sports Cars", in contrast with the specialised racing cars used in Grand Prix motor racing.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over time, the competing vehicles evolved away from their publicly available road car roots.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These are further broken down into: Hypercar (LMH or LMDh), LMP2 and LMGT3 (GT cars).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was part of the World Sportscar Championship every year from its inception in 1953 until its demise in 1992, except during the 1956, 1975–1979 and 1989–1990 seasons.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race was part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, and since 2012 it has been part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, winning Le Mans is often considered to be more important than winning the championship itself.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is also known as a leg of the informal Triple Crown of Motorsport which links Formula One, IndyCar, and sports car racing to represent a career achievement for drivers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Additionally, it is seen as a leg of the Triple Crown of endurance racing, which links the three largest sports car races together, with the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring forming the other legs.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1998, an endurance race called "Petit Le Mans" has been held every year as a 10-hour American version of the Le Mans 24 Hours.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] From 1999 to 2013, Petit Le Mans was part of the American Le Mans Series along with the 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, the IMSA SportsCar Championship (a merger of ALMS and the Rolex Sports Car Series) has held all four major American endurance classics, which teams can use to prepare for racing at Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Each car was required to have at least two seats.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, recently cars only need to have space to accommodate a second seat in the cockpit rather than the seat itself.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Two doors are allowed; open-cockpit cars do not require doors.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, all cars in the premier LMP1 category must have a roof for safety; open-cockpit cars are only permitted in the slightly slower LMP2 category.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2017, all prototype cars—Hypercar or LMP2—must have closed cockpits.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although all cars compete at the same time, as of 2021, there are separate classes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A prize is awarded to the winner of each class and the overall winner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The number of classes has varied over the years, but there are now three: Hypercar, LMP2, and LMGT3.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Successor to the Le Mans Prototype 1 (LMP1) is the custom-built Hypercar (LMH or LMDh) class.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is the top class and debuted in 2021.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new technical regulations are intended to prevent cost escalations while enabling greater variety in technical approaches and car aesthetics.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is followed by the LMP2 class where teams are obliged to run one of four approved chassis – ORECA, Ligier, Dallara, or Multimatic/Riley – mated with a standard 4.2-litre Gibson V8 engine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] ORECA is the most commonly used LMP2 chassis.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] LMP1 teams are not subjected to chassis and engine restrictions.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Their extra power, lower weight, and more complex aerodynamics result in much quicker lap times; LMP1 cars also may use hybrid technology.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The next class is LMGT3, which are similar to production-based sports cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Concept cars intended to test new automotive technologies may participate in the race under the "Garage 56" banner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such entries are classified in the race results, though are not expected to be competitive as their sole focus is to demonstrate experimental features.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, there were no rules on the number of car drivers or how long they could drive.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although almost all teams used two drivers in the early decades, some Le Mans drivers such as Pierre Levegh and Eddie Hall attempted to run the race solo, hoping to save time by not having to change drivers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until the 1980s, there were teams in which only two drivers competed, but by the end of the decade, the rules were changed to stipulate that at least three drivers must drive each car.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the 1990s, due to the speeds of the cars and the strain it puts on drivers, additional rules to reduce driver fatigue mandated that drivers could not drive for over 240 minutes (over 4 hours) and that no one driver could run for over 840 minutes (14 hours) total.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With careful management of driver stints, this makes it possible to complete the race with only two drivers (as Jeroen Bleekemolen and Cooper MacNeil did in 2014), although the vast majority of teams still continue to use three drivers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, the driving time rules were further changed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] If necessary, officials may require a drive time limit of 80 minutes of consecutive time behind the wheel and a minimum 30-minute rest break.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rule applies only if the air temperature is at least 32 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it has been a part of the World Sportscar Championship for most of its existence, the race has had different regulations for safety and competition reasons partly due to its length.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For many decades, cars had to run at least an hour into the race before they could refill fluids for the car, such as oil or coolant, except for fuel.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was an attempt by the ACO to help increase efficiency and reliability.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those who could not last the first hour without replacing lost fluids risked disqualification.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another rule unique to Le Mans is that cars must be switched off while refueling in the pits.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Not only is this safer and less of a fire hazard, but it is also another test of reliability, demanding a guaranteed ability to restart many times under race conditions.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another element of this rule is that mechanics are not allowed to work on the car while it is being refuelled (other than helping a driver in or out of the car), which has led teams to adapt innovative ways to decrease the time of these lengthy pit stops.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers can get out of the car and be replaced by another driver during refuelling.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those rules are also applied in the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] There are various long-standing traditions at Le Mans, including the waving of the French tricolor to start the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is usually preceded by a fly-over featuring jets trailing blue, white, and red smoke.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A similar flag tradition is track marshals waving safety flags during the race's final lap, congratulating the winners and other finishers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans was the venue for the first televised instance of a winning driver celebrating by spraying champagne instead of drinking it.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When Dan Gurney won the 1967 race with co-driver A.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt, the two drivers mounted the victory podium, and Gurney was handed a magnum of champagne.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Looking down, he saw Ford CEO Henry Ford II, team owner Carroll Shelby and their wives, as well as several journalists who had predicted disaster for the high-profile duo.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney shook the bottle and sprayed everyone nearby.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney autographed and gave the bottle of champagne to *Life* photographer Flip Schulke, who used it as a lamp for years before returning it to Gurney.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race has been cancelled ten times: in 1936 (a labour strike during the Great Depression) and between 1940 and 1948 (World War II).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race usually takes place on the second weekend of June, with qualifying and practice taking place on the Wednesday and Thursday before the race, following a car inspection on Monday and Tuesday.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Currently, these sessions are held in the evening, with two separate two-hour sessions held each night.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Friday serves as a day of rest, and a parade of all the drivers through Le Mans is held.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Test days held at the end of April or beginning of May served as a pre-qualification weeding out the slowest cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, in 2005 the exorbitant cost of transporting cars to and from Le Mans led organizers to move the test day to the first weekend of June.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Pre-qualification was eliminated in 2000, meaning that all competitors invited to the test would be allowed into the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2001 the Le Mans Legend races have mostly been part of the schedule, usually running exhibition races during qualifying days, a few hours prior to the sessions for the Le Mans entrants.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since its inception, the race has usually started at 4:00 p.m. local time (Central European Summer Time, UTC + 02:00) on Saturday.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, the car that covered the greatest distance from its starting position was the winner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is known to have caught out the Ford team in 1966.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a dominant 1–2 lead, the two cars slowed to allow for a photo opportunity at the finish line, with Ken Miles slightly ahead of Bruce McLaren.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, since McLaren's car had started much farther back on the grid than Miles's, McLaren's car had covered the greatest distance over the 24 hours.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With the margin of victory determined to be eight metres, McLaren and his co-driver, Chris Amon, were declared the winners.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decision cost Miles and Denny Hulme a victory.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Miles had already won the other two endurance races at Sebring and Daytona.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a win at Le Mans, he would have become the first man to win all three and the first to win them all in the same year.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The "greatest distance" rule was modified with the introduction of a rolling start in 1971.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Now, the car that completes the greatest distance as of the final lap's completion – where "greatest distance" is measured by the start/finish line for all competitors – wins.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When two cars finish the same number of laps, their finishing order is determined by the faster overall completion time.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This rule was used in the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans to determine the race winner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The top two finishers completed 355 laps, with only 13 seconds difference between them.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although "greatest distance run" determines the provisional order of finishers, additional requirements must be met for a car to be classified.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All classification requirements hold except in exceptional circumstances, as determined by the race stewards.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race traditionally began with what became known as the *Le Mans start*, in which cars were lined up along the length of the pits.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until 1962, cars lined up by engine capacity.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 1963, qualifying times determined the lineup.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starting drivers stood on the opposite side of the front stretch.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When the French flag dropped to signify the start, the drivers ran across the track, entered and started their cars without assistance, and drove away.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This became a safety issue in the late 1960s when some drivers ignored their safety harnesses, then a recent invention.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to drivers running the first few laps either improperly harnessed due to attempting to do it while driving or sometimes not even harnessed at all, leading to several deaths when cars were involved in accidents due to the bunched field at the start.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This starting method inspired Porsche to locate the ignition key switch to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In a left-hand drive car, this allowed the driver to use his left hand to start the engine and his right hand to put the transmission into gear, which in turn shaves off a few tenths of a second.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Stirling Moss developed another method for speeding up the start.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His car was waiting with first gear already engaged.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] He switched the starter on when he jumped in without depressing the clutch.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starter motor immediately jerked the car forward, but the engine did not start due to low RPM.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After a few seconds of motion, he pushed the clutch down, allowing the engine to speed up and start while the car was moving.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Feeling the Le Mans Start was unsafe, in the 1969 race, Jacky Ickx opposed it by walking across the track while his competitors ran.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although he was nearly hit by a faster competitor's car while walking, Ickx took the time to fasten his safety belts before pulling away.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Privateer John Woolfe died in an accident on the first lap of that race; Ickx won.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The traditional Le Mans start was changed for 1970.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars were still lined up along the pit wall, but the drivers were already inside and strapped in.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the dropping of the French tricolor, the drivers started their engines and drove away.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1971, a rolling start (sometimes known as an *Indianapolis start*) begins the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While the cars do still start out lined up against the pit wall, when the green flag is waved the cars pull away one by one to begin a formation lap behind the safety car; when that car returns to the pit lane, the starter waves the French flag to start the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit on which the 24 Hours of Le Mans is run is named the Circuit de la Sarthe, after the department that Le Mans is within.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It consists of both permanent track and public roads temporarily closed for the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1923, the track has been extensively modified, mostly for safety reasons, and now is 13.626 km (8.467 mi) in length.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it initially entered the town of Le Mans, the track was cut short to better protect spectators.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to the creation of the Dunlop Curve and Tertre Rouge corners before rejoining the old circuit on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another major change was on the Mulsanne itself in 1990 when the FIA decreed that it would no longer sanction any circuit that had a straight longer than 2 km (1.2 mi).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] To comply with this, two chicanes were added to the 6-kilometre-long (3.7 mi) straight, dividing it into three pieces about 2 km each.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The addition of the chicanes was further influenced by the fact that the speed of Welter Racing's WM P88, driven by French driver Roger Dorchy, had been timed at 407 km/h (253 mph) during the 1988 race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was the record speed before the addition of the chicanes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to the shorter length of the straights, the speed record at Le Mans now, after the introduction of the chicanes, is 366 km/h (227 mph).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Typically race cars achieve top speed of just under 320 km/h (200 mph) at the current track (with chicanes).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The public sections of the track differ from the permanent circuit, especially in comparison with the Bugatti Circuit which is inside the Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to heavy traffic, the public roads are not as smooth or well kept.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They also offer less grip because of the lack of soft-tyre rubber laid down from racing cars, though this only affects the first few laps of the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The roads are closed only within a few hours of the practice sessions and the race before being opened again almost as soon as the race is finished.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Workers have to assemble and dismantle safety barriers every year for the public sections.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was first run on 26 and 27 May 1923, through public roads around Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally planned to be a three-year event, as part of the Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup, with a winner being declared by the car which could go the farthest distance over three consecutive 24-hour races, this idea was abandoned in 1928.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Overall winners were declared for every year depending on who covered the furthest distance by the time 24 hours were up.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The early races were dominated by French, British, and Italian drivers, teams, and cars, with Bugatti, Bentley, and Alfa Romeo being the top brands.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Innovations in car design began appearing at the track in the late 1930s, with Bugatti and Alfa Romeo running highly aerodynamic bodywork to run down the Mulsanne Straight at faster speeds.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was cancelled in 1936 due to general strikes in France, and the outbreak of World War II in 1939 resulted in a ten-year hiatus.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the reconstruction of circuit facilities, the race was resumed in 1949 with renewed interest from major automobile manufacturers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 1949 was also Ferrari's first victory, the 166MM of Luigi Chinetti and Peter Mitchell-Thomson.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After the formation of the World Sportscar Championship in 1953, of which Le Mans was a part, Ferrari, Aston Martin, Mercedes-Benz, Jaguar and many others began sending multiple cars backed by their respective factories to compete for overall wins against their competitors.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This competitiveness sometimes resulted in tragedy, as in the 1955 Le Mans disaster during the 1955 race in which Pierre Levegh's car crashed into a crowd of spectators, killing more than 80 people.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The incident led to the widespread introduction of safety measures, not only at the circuit but elsewhere in the motorsport world.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The entire pit complex was razed and rebuilt further back following the accident, allowing the pit straight to be widened.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, there was still no barrier between the track and the pit lane.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Safety standards improved, but the cars got faster.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The move from open-cockpit roadsters to closed-cockpit coupés resulted in speeds of over 320 km/h (200 mph) on the Mulsanne.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford entered the picture with the GT40, finally ending Ferrari's dominance with four straight wins (1966–1969) before the 1960s ended and the cars and the race changed substantially.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In those years racing took a turn towards more extreme speeds and automotive designs.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This contributed to the replacement of the typical standing *Le Mans start* with a rolling *Indianapolis start*.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Purpose-built sportscars became the norm, with the traditional production-based cars now racing in lower classes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche was dominant throughout the decade with their 917, 935, and 936 models.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] French manufacturers Matra-Simca and Renault also gained success, with the first victories for the nation since the 1950 race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Notably, 1978 saw the first win of a turbocharged engine with the Renault Alpine A443.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decade is also remembered for strong performances from many privateer constructors, with two scoring the only victories for a privateer in the decade.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] John Wyer's Mirage won in 1975, while Jean Rondeau's self-titled chassis took 1980.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rest of the 1980s was known for the dominance by Porsche under the new Group C race car formula that encouraged fuel efficiency.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally running the effective 956, it was later replaced by the 962.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Both chassis were affordable enough for privateers to purchase them en masse, leading to the two model types winning six years in a row.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz returned to sports car racing, with Jaguar being the first to break Porsche's dominance with victories in 1988 and 1990 (with the XJR-9 and Jaguar XJR-12 respectively).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mercedes-Benz won in 1989, with what was seen as the latest incarnation of the elegant "Silver Arrows", the Sauber C9, while an influx of Japanese manufacturer interest saw prototypes from Nissan and Toyota.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In qualifying for the 1988 race, a WM Peugeot – built for speed, not meant to (and it did not) endure 24 hours – set the never surpassed speed trap record of 407 km/h (253 mph) in the *Ligne Droite des Hunaudières*, famous for its 6 km (3.7 mi) long straight.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda would be the first Japanese manufacturer to succeed, with their unique rotary-powered 787B winning in 1991.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1992 and 1993, Peugeot dominated the race with its Peugeot 905 as the Group C formula and World Sportscar Championship were fading in participation.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit would also undergo one of its most notable changes in 1990, when the 5 km long Mulsanne was modified to include two chicanes in order to stop speeds of more than 400 km/h (250 mph) from being reached again.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This began the ACO's trend to slow the cars on various portions of the track.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, speeds over 320 km/h (200 mph) are still regularly reached at various points on a lap.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the demise of the World Sportscar Championship, Le Mans saw a resurgence of production-based grand tourer cars.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Thanks to a loophole in the rules, Porsche succeeded in convincing the ACO that a Dauer 962 Le Mans supercar was a production car, allowing Porsche to race their Porsche 962 for one final time, dominating the field.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although the ACO attempted to close the loophole for 1995, newcomer McLaren would win the race in their supercar's first appearance thanks to the reliability of the BMW V12 powered F1 GTR, beating faster yet more trouble-prone prototypes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The trend would continue through the 1990s as more exotic supercars were built in order to skirt the ACO's rules regarding production-based race cars, leading to Porsche, Mercedes-Benz, Toyota, Nissan, Panoz, and Lotus entering the GT categories.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This culminated in the 1999 event, in which these GT cars were faced with the Le Mans Prototypes of BMW, Audi, Toyota and Ferrari.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] BMW would survive with the victory, their first and only overall Le Mans win to date.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Mercedes left sportscar racing indefinitely following three catastrophic though non-fatal crashes stemming from severe aerodynamic flaws with their CLR.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This strong manufacturer influence led the ACO to lend the Le Mans name to a sports car series in the United States in 1999, known as the American Le Mans Series, which ran until the end of the 2013 season after which it merged with Grand-Am to form the United SportsCar Championship.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Many major automobile manufacturers withdrew from sports car racing after 1999 due to the high cost.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Only Cadillac and Audi remained, and Audi easily dominated with the R8.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cadillac pulled out three years later, and attempts by Panoz, Chrysler, and MG to beat Audi all fell short.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After three victories in a row, Audi provided engine, team staff, and drivers to Bentley, a corporate partner, which had returned in 2001.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2003, the factory Bentley Speed 8s beat privateer Audis.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Chevrolet Corvette Racing Team and their C5-R won several times in the GTS class, finishing 1st and 2nd in 2001, 2002, and 2004.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They finished 2nd and 3rd in 2003 behind Ferrari.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the end of 2005, after five overall victories for the R8, and six to its V8 turbo engine, Audi took on a new challenge by introducing a diesel engined prototype known as the R10 TDI.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although not the first diesel to race, it was the first to win at Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This era saw other alternative fuel sources used, including bio-ethanol.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Peugeot decided to follow Audi's lead and pursue a diesel entry in 2007 with their 908 HDi FAP.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2008 race between the Audi R10 TDI and the Peugeot 908 HDi FAP, the Audi won by a margin of fewer than 10 minutes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For the 2009 24 Hours of Le Mans, Peugeot introduced a new energy-recovery system similar to the KERS used in Formula One.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aston Martin entered the LMP1 category, but still raced in GT1 with private teams.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi returned with the new R15 TDI, but Peugeot prevailed in its first overall win since 1993.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2010 running reaffirmed the race as a test of endurance and reliability.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Peugeot chose overall speed in adjusting their cars and engines to adhere to the 2010 regulations, while Audi chose reliability.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All four Peugeots had retired at the end of the race, three due to engine failure, while Audi finished 1–2–3.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2011 and 2012 races were marred by a series of accidents.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the Audi driven by Allan McNish crashed heavily in the first hour, barrel rolling into a tire wall shortly after the Dunlop Bridge.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At night, the defending race-winning Audi driven by Mike Rockenfeller crashed similarly between the Mulsanne and Indianapolis corners.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Neither driver was seriously injured, nor were any spectators.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The third Audi entry was driven by Marcel Fässler, André Lotterer, and Benoît Tréluyer won the race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 race saw two factory Toyotas replace Peugeot, which had withdrawn earlier, but one flipped at Mulsanne Corner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Driver Anthony Davidson suffered two broken vertebrae but could exit the car himself.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Shortly after sunset, the other Toyota retired with mechanical difficulties, leading to another Audi victory.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race became the premier round of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, attempting to make a world championship for endurance racing again.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012, the race became the centerpiece of the FIA World Endurance Championship, the successor to the ILMC.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 event was the first time the race was won by a hybrid electric vehicle, which was the Audi R18 e-tron quattro.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Regulations were changed for 2014, notably with a requirement that all LMP1 cars must be closed-cockpit, some changes to the hybrid system, and the introduction of the slow zone system.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche returned to Le Mans in 2014 with a new factory LMP1 program, and Nissan returned to run an LMP1 program in 2015.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi withdrew from racing at the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2016 and Nissan after only one attempt in 2015.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche won the race in 2015, 2016, and 2017 with its hybrid 919, and remains the most successful manufacturer at Le Mans, with 19 overall victories.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, changes were made to the LMP2 regulations on cockpit and chassis, meaning all prototype cars must be closed-cockpit.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota won their first Le Mans with Fernando Alonso, Sébastien Buemi and Kazuki Nakajima driving.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2020 also saw the race held behind closed doors for the first time due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the introduction of the Hypercar class, a class that allows for Le Mans Hypercars and from 2023 onwards also LMDh cars to participate.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the race postponed once again, this time until August.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For 2021 and 2022, non-hybrid LMP1 cars were allowed to participate as "grandfathered" LMP1 cars, although only Alpine would make use of this.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Other entries in the hypercar class were Toyota and privateer team Glickenhaus.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new Hypercar regulations allowed manufacturers more freedom with the design, leading to cars such as the wingless Peugeot 9X8 entering in 2022, with other unique designs expected to be added.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The LMP2 regulations were extended to 2027 with the next generation LMP2 cars to be introduced in 2028.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2028 will likely also see the introduction of hydrogen powered prototypes.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The former LMGTE class was also replaced by LMGT3 in 2024.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans has seen many innovations in automotive design to counteract the circuit's difficulties.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These have either been dictated by rules or have been attempts by manufacturers to outwit the competition.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Some innovations were incorporated into the everyday automobile.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] One of the keys to Le Mans is top speed due to the long straights that dominate the circuit.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has meant cars have attempted to achieve the maximum speeds possible instead of relying on downforce for the turns.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While early competitors' cars were street cars with their bodywork removed to reduce weight, innovators like Bugatti developed cars that saw the beginnings of aerodynamics.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Nicknamed *tanks* due to their similarity to military tanks in World War I, these cars used simple curves to cover all the car's mechanical elements and increase top speed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Once Le Mans returned after World War II, most manufacturers would adopt closed bodies streamlined for better aerodynamics.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A notable example of the changes brought about by aerodynamics are the 1950 entries by Briggs Cunningham.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cunningham entered two 1950 Cadillac Coupe de Villes, one nearly stock and the other completely rebodied in a streamlined aluminum shape developed by Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation that looked so unusual that it was nicknamed "Le Monstre" by the French press.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The smoothing of body shapes and fairing-in of various parts of the machine brought about by the continual search for reduction of aerodynamic drag led to a separation from Grand Prix cars, which rarely had large bodywork.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] As the years went on, bodywork became all-enveloping, while at the same time lighter.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The larger bodywork with spoilers was able to provide more downforce for the turns without increasing the drag, allowing cars to maintain high speeds.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Extended bodywork would usually concentrate on the car's rear, usually being termed *long tail*.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The bodywork also began to cover the cockpit for less drag.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, open cockpits would come and go over the years as rules varied.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aerodynamics reached its peak in 1989 before the Mulsanne Straight was modified.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] During the 1988 race, the crew of a Peugeot powered WM prototype taped over the engine openings, allowing Roger Dorchy to set a recorded speed of 407 km/h (253 mph) down the Mulsanne.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, the car was almost undrivable elsewhere on the circuit.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The engine was soon destroyed from a lack of cooling.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, for the 1989 event, the Mercedes-Benz C9 reached 400 km/h (249 mph) under qualifying conditions.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A wide variety of engines have competed at Le Mans in attempts to achieve greater speed and fuel economy and to spend less time in the pits.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Engine sizes have also varied greatly, with the smallest engines being a mere 569 cc (Simca Cinq) and the largest upwards of 8,000 cc (SRT Viper GTS-R).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Supercharging was an early innovation for increasing output, first being raced in 1929, while turbocharging first appeared in 1974.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The first entry without a piston engine came in 1963, when Rover partnered with British Racing Motors to run a gas turbine car with mixed success, an effort they repeated in 1965.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The American Howmet Corporation attempted to employ a turbine in 1968 with even less success: although the engines offered great power, they were hot and not fuel-efficient.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another non-piston engine that appeared was the Wankel engine, otherwise known as the rotary engine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Used exclusively (in automotive applications) by Mazda since its introduction in 1970, the compact rotary engine suffered from fuel economy problems, yet eventually achieved the success that the turbines had not.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After many years of development, Mazda finally became the only winner of the race not to have a piston-powered engine, as it took the 1991 event with the 787B.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative fuel sources have also played a part in more normal engine designs, with the first non-gasoline car appearing in 1949.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Delettrez Special was powered by a diesel engine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, a second diesel appeared in the form of the M.A.P. the following year.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although diesel was used on several occasions, it was not until 2006 that a prominent manufacturer, Audi, invested in diesel; the company's R10 TDI was a success.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ethanol fuel appeared in 1980 in a modified Porsche 911, leading to a class win.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative biological fuel sources returned again in 2004 with Team Nasamax's DM139-Judd.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2008, biofuels (10% ethanol for petrol engines and biodiesel for diesel engines) were allowed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi was the first to use next-generation 10% BTL biodiesel developed by Shell and manufactured from biomass.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 2009, new regulations allowed hybrid vehicles with either KERS or TERS (Kinetic/Thermal Energy Recovery System) setups.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, only electrical (i.e., battery) energy storage was allowed, ruling out flywheel-based energy recovery.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars with KERS were allowed to race in 2009 under specific classification rules.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2010, they have competed for points and the championship.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012 the first KERS-equipped car won; the Audi R18 e-tron with a flywheel hybrid system by Williams Hybrid Power activated and drove the front wheels.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was only allowed in certain zones after the car had accelerated to at least 120 km/h to cancel out the acceleration advantage that all-wheel-drive cars could gain out of corners.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the same year, Toyota also started with a hybrid car, the TS030, which used KERS to power its rear wheels, meaning its usage was not restricted.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2025, the Automobile Club de l’Ouest is planning to introduce a hydrogen-electric prototype class.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This class will be a one-design class with a chassis provided by Red Bull Advanced Technologies-Oreca and a powertrain supplied by GreenGT.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The development of the hydrogen fuel cells powering the cars will be left to the teams themselves.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] According to the ACO's president Pierre Fillon, there is also a possibility of the cars being powered by a hydrogen combustion engine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The performance of the class is expected to be competitive with the top Hypercar class.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Toyota unveiled new GR LH2 prototype for Gazoo Racing Europe.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With increased speeds around the track, brakes become a key issue for teams attempting to safely bring their cars down to a slow enough speed to make the Mulsanne Corner turn.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Disc brakes were first seen in 1953 when the Jaguar C-Type raced at Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1955 the Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR introduced the air brake using a large opening hood on the rear of the car.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford used a quick change brake rotor in 1966 to achieve their first victory at Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 1980s, anti-lock braking systems became standard on most Group C cars as a safety measure, making it less likely that cars lose control at high speeds.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the late 1990s, reinforced carbon-carbon brakes were adopted for better stopping power.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over the years, many manufacturers have managed to take the overall win, while even more have taken class wins.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most successful marque in the history of the race is Porsche, which has taken nineteen overall victories, including seven in a row from 1981 to 1987 and 107 class victories.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi is next with thirteen wins, and Ferrari follows with eleven, also including six in a row from 1960 to 1965.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2000 Audi has dominated the event, winning 13 times in 15 years of participation.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi and Team Joest have had two hat-tricks, the first being in 2000, 2001, and 2002.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, Toyota won five races in a row and Bentley, Alfa Romeo, and Ford all won four races in a row, with Bentley recording two additional victories in other years.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota became only the second Japanese marque to win, following Mazda in 1991.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda is also the only company to win with a rotary engine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After Porsche's total of 107 class victories, Ferrari has 37, and Aston Martin, Audi, and Chevrolet each have 14.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three drivers stand apart for their number of victories.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, Jacky Ickx held the record at six, scoring victories between 1969 and 1982, earning him honorary citizenship to the town of Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His frequent racing partner, Derek Bell, trailing by a single win, with five.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, Tom Kristensen has beaten this record with nine wins between 1997 and 2013, including six in a row.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three-time winner Woolf Barnato (1928 to 1930), Tazio Nuvolari (1933), Luis Fontés (1935), American racing legend A.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt (1967), Nico Hülkenberg (2015), and Fernando Alonso (2018–2019) are the only drivers to have won every Le Mans in which they participated.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Henri Pescarolo won the race four times, and holds the record for the most Le Mans appearances at 33.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Japan's Yojiro Terada was active as a driver until 2008, and holds the record for the most Le Mans starts without an overall win.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Claude Ballot-Léna holds the most class victories other than Kristensen with seven wins in GT class cars between 1970 and 1986.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Graham Hill is the only driver to win the so-called *Triple Crown of Motorsport*, winning the Indianapolis 500 (1966), Monaco Grand Prix (1963, 1964, 1965, 1968, 1969), and the 24 Hours of Le Mans (1972).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Le Mans has seen many fatal accidents due partly to the very high-speed nature of all variants of the track throughout history.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The largest one was in 1955 when at least 81 spectators (exact number unknown, many sources estimate 83) and driver Pierre Levegh were killed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the wake of the disaster, many races were cancelled, including the Grand Prix races in Germany, Spain, France and Switzerland (the latter as a part of a blanket ban on motorsport round-track races that was maintained until 2022).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The accident led to safety regulations in all motorsports for both driver and spectator protection.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Almost all decades in which Le Mans has been run have seen many horrific accidents, such as in 1972 when Jo Bonnier was catapulted into a forest surrounding the circuit after hitting a privately entered Ferrari near the Indianapolis section; Bonnier was killed instantly.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1980s was a decade where some of the race's worst-ever accidents occurred.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Armco barriers had been installed along the straight in 1969, there were still no chicanes on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] It was here that almost all of the worst accidents occurred during that time.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1981, Belgian Thierry Boutsen crashed on the Mulsanne Straight in his WM-Peugeot, killing a marshal.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the same race, Frenchman Jean-Louis Lafosse was also killed on the Mulsanne Straight when his Rondeau suffered a suspension failure, steered very suddenly to the right, and slammed into the Armco barrier on the driver's side at extreme speeds.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1984 race saw British privateer John Sheldon crashing at more than 320 km/h (200 mph) at the Mulsanne Kink; his Aston Martin V8 powered Nimrod tore through the Armco barriers into the trees.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The resulting explosion was so violent that the woods next to the track caught fire.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Sheldon survived with severe burns, a track marshal was killed; two others were also severely injured.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Sheldon's teammate, American Drake Olson in the second Nimrod-Aston Martin, who was following him down the straight, crashed heavily after running over Sheldon's bodywork; he went into severe shock but survived with minor injuries.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The field was under the safety car for over an hour while the crash site was cleared, and the destroyed Armco barriers were replaced.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, a similar accident befell Briton Dudley Wood in a Porsche 962 during practice.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The impact of the car against the Armco, considering Wood was doing more than 370 km/h (230 mph), was so hard that it cracked the engine block.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, John Nielsen flipped his Sauber-Mercedes while going over the Mulsanne hump at more than 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The car landed on its roof and was destroyed, but Nielsen escaped without injury.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1986, Jo Gartner drove a Porsche 962C into the Mulsanne barriers and was killed instantly after the car rolled multiple times, vaulted some Armco barriers, and knocked down a telegraph pole.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Moreover, in 1987, American Price Cobb crashed a works Porsche 962C after slipping on oil during Wednesday practice.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The fuel tank exploded and the car burned to the ground, but Cobb escaped without injury.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Gartner's fatal accident remained the most recent death in the race until Allan Simonsen's crash in 2013.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, there was one fatality during a practice session in 1997 (Sebastien Enjolras).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1999, the Mercedes-Benz CLRs suffered from aerodynamic instability leading to cars getting airborne and flipping backwards, no less than three times.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] After initially happening on Thursday to the #4 car, Mercedes rebuilt the chassis on Friday and claimed to have solved the problem, only for it to occur again at warmup on Saturday.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Mark Webber was the unlucky driver whose car flipped on both occasions.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The last and most damaging accident occurred during the race itself when Peter Dumbreck's CLR #5 became airborne, flying over the safety fencing and landing in the woods several metres away.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] No drivers were severely hurt in any of the three accidents.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, Mercedes-Benz withdrew its remaining entry and ended its entire sportscar programme to focus on F1 and the upcoming new DTM.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2011, two horrific accidents occurred to two of the three factory Audis in the LMP1 class.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 3 car driven by Allan McNish collided with one of the Ferrari GT cars, resulting in McNish's car smashing into the tyre wall and being thrown into the air at the Dunlop chicanes, resulting in pieces of bodywork flying over and nearly hitting many photographers on the other side of the barrier.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the eleventh hour of the race, another accident occurred to the No.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 1 car driven by Mike Rockenfeller when he had contact with another Ferrari GT car.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the runup to Indianapolis corner, Rockenfeller's Audi was sent into the outside barrier at over 270 km/h (170 mph).
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Only the main cockpit safety cell of the car remained, along with major damage being done to the barriers that needed to be repaired before the race was resumed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Audi had switched to a closed-cockpit car starting in 2011, a decision credited for the fact that neither driver was injured.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 2014 regulations required all cars to be closed-cockpit due to the 2011 accident.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2012, Anthony Davidson, driving for the returning Toyota team in a Toyota TS030 Hybrid, collided with a Ferrari 458 GT2 of Piergiuseppe Perazzini, and became airborne before crashing into the tyre barrier of the Mulsanne Corner at high speed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The Ferrari also ended up in the barrier, flipping and coming to a halt on its roof.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2013, Allan Simonsen died after crashing into the barriers at Tertre Rouge.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] When the car collided with the guard rail, a mature tree had been touching the barrier, thereby preventing the guard rail from performing its safety function.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Motors TV covered the Le Mans 24 Hours in its entirety in 2006 and 2007, including coverage of the scrutineering, qualifying, driver parade, warmup, and race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the United States, FOX owned SPEED Channel, followed by Fox Sports 1 and Fox Sports 2 aired complete race coverage live either on-air or online through a combination of coverage from the French host broadcaster and its own pit reporting crew for several years.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A United States television deal was not done for the 2018–19 WEC Super Season because of a renegotiation of its European contract.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2008, Eurosport secured a multi-year deal to show the entire race, including the qualifying and the motorcycle race.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Every hour of the 2008 race was broadcast in segments on the main channel and Eurosport 2.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, a couple of hours were missed in recent years due to scheduling clashes with other sporting events.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In addition, Eurosport provided live streaming on its website to subscribers.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2009, Eurosport and Eurosport 2 have covered all the action, and beginning in 2018, Eurosport gained United States broadcast rights for the World Endurance Championship for the race only on Motor Trend, a channel also owned by Eurosport's parent company.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Qualifying and practices aired on a direct-to-consumer streaming platform from Motor Trend magazine.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In Australia in 2012, Ten Sport showed the race live and in full online.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The race is also broadcast (in English) on the radio by Radio Le Mans.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2001, the ACO has allowed the "Le Mans Legend" event to participate on the full Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] These exhibition races involve classic cars that had previously run at Le Mans or are similar to those.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Each year, a particular era of cars may participate, with the featured era changing from year to year.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Though most drivers in this event are amateurs, some noted professional drivers have appeared to race cars they had previously run, such as Stirling Moss and Derek Bell.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Starting in 2002, the "Le Mans Classic" has been held as a biennial event on the full 13 km (8.1 mi) circuit in July.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The races take place over a full 24-hour day/night cycle, with starts on set times allowing cars from the same era to compete simultaneously.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A team typically consists of a car in each class.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The team with the most points accumulated over five or six classes is declared the overall winner.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The classes are based on the era in which the cars would have competed.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The exact class requirements are re-evaluated for every event since the age for the youngest entries is shifted by two years for each event.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the first event, five classes ran more short races; later events have featured six classes running fewer but longer races.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Drivers are required to have an FIA International Competition license.
[src:amersfoort/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] This event also includes a large Concours d'Elegance and auction.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] The **A1** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] The road connects the capital city of Amsterdam, near the interchange of Watergraafsmeer, with the German border, near Oldenzaal and Bad Bentheim, and the German Autobahn BAB 30.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] On its way, it crosses four provinces: North Holland, Utrecht, Gelderland and Overijssel.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] The section of the road between its start at the interchange Watergraafsmeer, and the interchange of Hoevelaken near Amersfoort, is also a European route: the E231.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] This section of the A1 is the complete E231 route; the E231 does not consist of any other road or section.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] Between the interchange Hoevelaken and the German border (and beyond, along the BAB 30), the European route E30 follows the A1 motorway.
[src:amersfoort/a1-motorway-netherlands] This European route is a so-called A-Class West-East European route, going from Cork in Ireland all the way to Omsk in Russia.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The **A28 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] It is approximately 188 kilometers in length.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The A28 traverses the Dutch provinces of Utrecht, Gelderland, Overijssel, Drenthe and Groningen.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The road connects the cities of Utrecht, Amersfoort, Zwolle, Assen, and Groningen.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The A28 motorway's southern terminus is in the city of Utrecht, at an intersection with the Waterlinieweg, an important arterial road through the eastern part of the city.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] Major motorway junctions can be found at the interchanges Rijnsweerd near Utrecht (A27), Hoevelaken near Amersfoort (A1), Hattemerbroek near Zwolle (motorway A50 / highway N50), Lankhorst near Meppel (A32) and Hoogeveen near Hoogeveen (A37).
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The northern terminus is at the traffic light controlled intersection of Julianaplein near Groningen (motorway A7 / highway N7).
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The A28, however, is not the most direct connection between Utrecht and Groningen.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The route via Lelystad and Heerenveen, following the A27, A6 and the A7, is some 10 kilometers shorter.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] Groningen is not signed at the southern terminus of the motorway to avoid confusion.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] Groningen first appears on the signs near exit Soesterberg.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] The A28 motorway generally has 2x2 lanes, except for a short section just east of Utrecht where shoulder running is allowed during rushhour, and the section between the junctions Hattemerbroek (A50/N50) and Lankhorst (A32).
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] In the city of Zwolle, narrow additional lanes are added in the median that can be opened depending on traffic flow, whereas three permanent lanes are available between exit 21 and junction Lankhorst.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] Between the interchange Hoevelaken near Amersfoort and the terminus at Julianaplein in Groningen, the A28 is also a European route: the E232.
[src:amersfoort/a28-motorway-netherlands] This section of the A28 is the complete E232 route; the E232 does not consist of any other road or section.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Hunter gatherers set up camps in the Amersfoort region in the Mesolithic period.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Archaeologists have found traces of these camps, such as the remains of hearths, and sometimes microlithic flint objects, to the north of the city.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Remains of settlements dating to 1000 BC have been found in the Amersfoort area.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The name Amersfoort, after a ford in the Amer River, today called the Eem, first appeared in the 11th century.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The city grew around what is now the *Hof*, where the Bishops of Utrecht established a court in order to control the "Gelderse Vallei" area.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] It was granted city rights in 1259 by the bishop of Utrecht, Henry I van Vianden.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] A first defensive wall, made of brick, was completed around 1300 but expansion led to the construction of a new wall in 1380, which was completed around 1450.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The Koppelpoort, a combined land and water gate, is part of this second wall.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The first wall was demolished and houses were built in its place.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Today's *Muurhuizen* (wallhouses) Street is located where the first wall stood.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The *Onze-Lieve-Vrouwentoren* (Tower of Our Lady) is one of the tallest medieval church towers in the Netherlands at 98 metres (322 ft).
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] When it was built, it was the middle point of The Netherlands, it was exactly built in the center and a reference for the Dutch grid system.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The nickname of the tower is Lange Jan ('Long John').
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The construction of the tower and the church was started in 1444.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The church was destroyed by an explosion in 1787, but the tower survived, and the layout of the church still can be discerned today through the use of different types of stone in the pavement of the open space that was created.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] It is now the reference point of the RD coordinate system, the coordinate grid used by the Dutch topographical service: the RD coordinates are (155.000, 463.000).
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The inner city of Amersfoort has been preserved well since the Middle Ages.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Apart from the Onze-Lieve-Vrouwetoren, the Koppelpoort, and the *Muurhuizen* (Wall-houses), there is also the Sint-Joriskerk (Saint George's church), the canal-system with its bridges, as well as medieval and other old buildings; many are designated as national monuments.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] In the Middle Ages, Amersfoort was an important centre for the textile industry, and there were a large number of breweries.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Jews also lived in Amersfoort in the Middle Ages, before being expelled from the province in 1546 and beginning to return to the city in 1655.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The nickname for Amersfoort, *Keistad* (boulder-city), originates in the *Amersfoortse Kei*, a 9-tonne (19,842 lb) boulder that was dragged from the Soest moors into the city in 1661 by 400 people because of a bet between two landowners.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The people got their reward when the winner bought everyone beer and pretzels.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Other nearby towns then nicknamed the people of Amersfoort *Keientrekker* (boulder-puller).
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] This story embarrassed the inhabitants, and they buried the boulder in the city in 1672, but after it was found again in 1903 it was placed in a prominent spot as a monument.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] There are not many boulders in the Netherlands, so it can be regarded as an icon.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] One of the six Dutch towns established in the 17th century in what is now Brooklyn was called "Nieuw Amersfoort" (New Amersfoort).
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The original patentees were Wolfert Gerritse van Kouwenhoven and Andries Hudde.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Unlike other Dutch names which were retained up to the present, Nieuw Amersfoort is now called "Flatlands".
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] In the 18th century, the city flourished because of the cultivation of tobacco, but from about 1800 onwards began to decline.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The decline was halted by the establishment of the first railway connection in 1863, and some years later, by the building of a substantial number of infantry and cavalry barracks, which were needed to defend the western cities of the Netherlands.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] After the 1920s, growth stalled again; in 1970, the national government designated Amersfoort, then numbering some 70,000 inhabitants, as a "growth city".
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] During the First World War, the area of Amersfoort with nearby Soesterberg and Zeist was one of the places in The Netherlands where many refugees from Belgium were sheltered.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The "Belgenmonument", located in the vicinity of the former refugee camp Elisabethdorp, commemorates this period and the hardships of the Belgian refugees.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Since Amersfoort was the largest garrison town in the Netherlands before the outbreak of the Second World War, with eight barracks, and part of the main line of defence, the whole population of then 43,000 was evacuated at the start of the invasion by the Germans in May 1940.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] After four days of battle, the population was allowed to return.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] There was a functioning Jewish community in the town, at the beginning of the war numbering about 700 people.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Half of them were deported and killed, mainly in Auschwitz and Sobibor.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] In 1943, the synagogue, dating from 1727, was severely damaged on the orders of the then Nazi-controlled city government.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] It was restored and opened again after the war, and has been served since by a succession of rabbis.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] There was a Nazi concentration camp near the city of Amersfoort during the war.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The camp, officially called *Polizeiliches Durchgangslager Amersfoort* (Police Transit Camp Amersfoort), better known as *Kamp Amersfoort*, was actually located in the neighbouring municipality of Leusden.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] After the war the leader of the camp, Joseph Kotälla, served a life sentence in prison.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Some of the victims of the camp are buried in Rusthof cemetery near the town.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Among the victims were prisoners of war from the Soviet Union, including 101 Central Asians, mostly Uzbeks.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Locals would commemorate them, but the identity of the 101 soldiers was not known, until journalist Remco Reiding started investigating this case in 1999, after hearing about the cemetery.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Amongst the few remaining people who witnessed the 101 soldiers is Henk Broekhuizen.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Amersfoort had its own professional football (soccer) club named HVC Amersfoort.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] It was founded on 30 July 1973, but disbanded on 30 June 1982 because of financial problems.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The city also hosted the riding part of the modern pentathlon event for the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Amersfoort also hosted the Dutch Open (tennis) tournament from 2002 until its end in 2008.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The city is also home to the baseball and softball club Quick Amersfoort.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The club's top men's baseball team plays in the Honkbal Hoofdklasse, the highest level of Dutch baseball.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] It is the hometown of field and track athlete Femke Bol.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The *DierenPark Amersfoort* zoo was founded in 1948.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] As of 2020, Amersfoort had a total population of 157,276 people.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Bus services are provided by 2 firms: U-OV and Syntus.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Syntus provides services in town and the entirety of the province Utrecht, save for the bus to the city Utrecht, which is provided by U-OV.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] All three serve direct trains to Utrecht Centraal and Zwolle.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Amersfoort Centraal and Amersfoort Schothorst also have direct service to Den Haag Centraal, Amsterdam Centraal, and Amsterdam Zuid.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] Amersfoort Centraal further serves direct trains to Enschede, Rotterdam Centraal, Schiphol Airport, Leeuwarden, Groningen, Ede–Wageningen and Berlin Hauptbahnhof.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The river Eem (pronounced roughly "aim") begins in Amersfoort, and the town has a port for inland water transport.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The Eem connects to the nearby *Eemmeer* (Lake Eem).
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The Valleikanaal drains the eastern Gelderse Vallei and joins with other sources to form the Eem in Amersfoort.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The municipal council of Amersfoort consists of 39 seats.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The municipal elections are held every 4 years.
[src:amersfoort/amersfoort] The city has a court of first instance (*kantongerecht*).
